observations.recommendation:
In view of the foregoing, we recommended and Management agreed to:
(a) require the Municipal Accountant to record appropriate amounts of impairment loss on overdue Receivable accounts in accordance with paragraph 87 of IPSAS No. 41;
(b) cause the immediate collection of the Accounts Receivable amounting to ₱40,000.00 under the name of the establishment which the Municipality still engaged official transactions;
(c) employ all appropriate remedies to recover overdue receivables, including issuance of demand letters and initiating legal proceedings, if necessary; and
(d) request for an authority from COA to write-off dormant receivables following the requirements stated under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We reiterated our previous year recommendation and Management agreed to instruct the:
(a) Municipal Treasurer to employ effective collection strategies by updating and posting the notice of delinquency for property taxes at designated areas and conduct massive campaign and public information dissemination on the value of paying taxes; and if warranted, enforce the provision of Section 254(b) of the RA No. 7160 in the collection of delinquent taxes;
(b) Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records on RPT/SET receivables in order to report reliably the said accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
(a) continue to comply with the allocation/attribution and utilization of the prescribed budget for GAD and the preparation of a relevant GAD Budget and Plan pursuant to the pertinent laws and regulations on GAD;
(b) issue an Executive Order installing the required structures and composition of GFPS;
(c) create GAD M&E Team that will assess the overall effectiveness and efficiency of gender mainstreaming efforts; and
(d) timely submit to the Audit Team the GAD Accomplishment Report in compliance with COA Circular No. 2014-001.

We reiterated our recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct:

the Municipal Accountant to –
strictly observe the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;

to issue the necessary demand letters to the accountable officers/persons, requiring them to settle their respective outstanding cash advances;

avoid the recurrence of similar lapses, endeavor to strengthen the internal control system for cash advances which would assure that cash advances are liquidated or reported on as soon as the purpose of the same is served, in compliance with Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 97-002;

exhaust all remedies/actions for the recovery and/or enforcement of liquidation of the subject long overdue outstanding cash advances; and

file a request for authority to write off all dormant unliquidated cash advances to the COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, if warranted.

the Municipal Treasurer to strictly observe the timely liquidation of cash advances for payroll within the prescribed period to prevent the accumulation of unliquidated cash advances at any given period and ensure that all cash advances are fully liquidated at year-end.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct –

the Public Employment Services Office (PESO) Manager-

to ensure that copy of the Memorandum of Understanding between the funding/source agency and the LGU are immediately secured for the adoption of the Early Procurement Activities (EPA) which will be the basis of the BAC to promptly initiate the procurement undertaking in the implementation of similar project in the future;

ensure the monitoring of the project and preparation/submission of the regular quarterly and annual progress reports as required by the funding agency;


the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant, in the implementation of similar future projects, ensure the timely preparation and submission of the corresponding liquidation reports and refund of the unutilized fund, if any, to the funding/source agencies within the prescribed period.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:

 encourage the Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer (MSWDO) to continue searching for innovative approach and strategy in the implementation of GAD activities which may be undertaken even in times of COVID 19 pandemic;

direct other Department Heads to collaborate with MSWDO in crafting feasible program/projects/activities (PPAs) workable in times of calamity;

motivate the officials/employees responsible in the implementation of GAD PPAs to continue the strict observance of the abovementioned regulations to maintain the LGU’s satisfactory compliance thereto; and

instruct the GAD Focal Person to continue to develop and implement more GAD related programs/activities that advocate women empowerment, promote gender equality and improve the welfare and protection of rights of women.

1.17. We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct –
a. the Municipal Social Welfare Officer (MSWO) to be more diligent in the preparation of payrolls based on the approved list of qualified beneficiaries and implementation of financial assistance of same nature in the future to avoid incurrence of similar lapses;
b. the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant, in the implementation of similar forthcoming projects, to (a) closely coordinate with the MSWDO in facilitating the review of payroll base on DSWD approved list of beneficiaries to prevent the inclusion of unqualified recipients in the payroll; and (b) consistently observe, monitor compliance on timely submission of liquidation reports and refund, if any, of unutilized fund to the source agency to help maximize the timely and efficient utilization of limited government resources.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the acting MENRO to 

comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by collecting only that garbage that are properly segregated; 

(b) encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes; 

(c) strictly enforce the use of Material Recovery Facility in barangay levels for final sorting, segregation, composting, and recycling so that only the residual wastes are transferred to Municipality’s station area; 

(d) ensure that only residual wastes are being collected by the MCWMC as stipulated in the MOA in order to avoid payment of costly hauling and tipping fee; and 

(e) provide a certain parcel of land appropriate for the implementation of its solid waste management activities, projects and programs.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Market Committee to 

(a) review and submit proposals on revision of market code to the Sangguniang Bayan which should include all the necessary provisions on the market operation; 

(b) prepare and submit to the Audit Team the monitoring report on the collection of fees from market stall rentals as of December 31, 2019; 

(c) strictly manage the public market operation particularly on the execution and implementation of contracts; and 

(d) monitor and intensify collections of market stall rentals

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor 

(a) require the Municipal Budget Officer to desist from charging claims/expenditures incurred in previous years but charged to current year appropriation; 

(b) cause the refund of the total amount of ₱1,013,929.90 representing unauthorized expenditure in CY 2018; 

(c) designate/assign only one municipal official who will approve and release gas slip request for control purposes; and 

(d) require the maintenance of logbook by the designated approving/releasing official for the recording of the gas slip approved and issued.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Business Permit and License (BPL) Officer and the OIC Municipal Treasurer to

(a) strictly comply with the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code covered by SB Resolution No. 111 S-2011 in the assessment and collection of business taxes; 

(b) apply all alternative procedures and efforts to be able to establish the correct amount of gross sales/receipts of every business establishment in the locality; 

 (c) refrain from assessing business tax dues based on verbally declared gross sales/receipts; 

 (d) require business establishment to submit original copies of Sworn Statement of Gross Sales/Receipts and the true photocopy of Income Tax Returns to check the correctness of paid business taxes; and 

(e) cause the collection of the amounts of ₱113,312.50 and ₱28,667.85 initially determined as understatement in business taxes of Pantoc Hardware and Construction and Sergie Trading, respectively.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to ensure that check and balance and financial control procedures are in place by requiring the:

Municipal Treasurer to directly release checks to the Payees and submit  all disbursement vouchers and supporting documents pertaining thereto to the Office of the Municipal Accountant including the unsubmitted DVs and SDs;

Disbursing Official to 

pay claims of salaries and wages directly to claimants; and
require authorization letters from the payee and identification card of person other than the payee/claimant; 
Human Resource Management to require submission of accomplishment reports not only the DTR for the period rendered before preparing the payroll; 
Management should also subject the daily time records (DTRs) of the casual/contractual personnel to biometric machine, if feasible; and
Municipal Accountant to ensure that 

all disbursements/ expenditures incurred are recorded in the books within the period of incurrence; and 

DVs and payrolls are evidenced by necessary supporting documents.

